	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The entry is as much an experience to be had as a game in the traditional sense. It's okay to not like it, not see it, or not find it funny. Unorthodox designs can't possibly cater to everybody. That's sometimes the price for doing something exactly the way you want it. No big deal. <br /><br />But if someone had an entry in the anthology and dedicated its introduction to ruining the intent of <em>somebody elses</em>' work, then that would indeed be poor judgment, with tendencies towards bullying. <br /><br />Just trust the author to know what's best for <em>their</em> work, even if you personally don't see it.<br /><br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">But I am annoyed by the premise that the menu is part of the game</div><br />I don't think anyone says it's part of the game. But it <em>affects</em> the range of first experiences you have with the game. So as i see it, it's the other way around. You shouldn't enforce a description that alters the experience of the game in a way the author hadn't intended.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


